07261nam a22010215i 9783110634822DE-B159720230228123812.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||230228t20192020gw     fo  d z      eng d  a2019948511  a97831106348227 a10.1515/97831106348222doi  a(DE-B1597)506934  a(OCoLC)1135589870  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE00aDS146.S34bA58 2020 7aHIS0220002bisacsh00aAntisemitism in the North :bHistory and State of Research /ced. by Jonathan Adams, Cordelia Heß. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter, c[2019] 4c©2020  a1 online resource (XIV, 302 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aReligious Minorities in the North : History, Politics, and Culture ,x2627-440X ;v100tFrontmatter -- tAcknowledgements -- tTable of Contents -- tIllustrations -- tContributors -- tIntroduction -- t1. Nordic Otherness -- tAntisemitism without Jews -- t2. "Untilled Field" or "Barren Terrain"? -- t3. William of Norwich in Iceland -- t4. Iceland -- t5. Beyond Shylock -- tThe State of Research on Antisemitism -- t6. Chronicles of a History Foretold -- t7. The Study of Antisemitism in Finland -- t8. A Marginal Phenomenon? -- t9. Norwegian Antisemitism after 1945 -- t10. Antisemitism in Sweden -- tPerceptions, Encounters, and the Presence of Antisemitism -- t11. Jerusalem in the North Atlantic -- t12. Jews in Greenland -- t13. Antisemitisms in the Twenty-First Century -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 aOpen Accessuhttps://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_abf2funrestricted online access2star  aIs research on antisemitism even necessary in countries with a relatively small Jewish population? Absolutely, as this volume shows. Compared to other countries, research on antisemitism in the Nordic countries (Denmark, the Faroe Islands, Finland, Greenland, Iceland, Norway, and Sweden) is marginalized at an institutional and staffing level, especially as far as antisemitism beyond German fascism, the Second World War, and the Holocaust is concerned. Furthermore, compared to scholarship on other prejudices and minority groups, issues concerning Jews and anti-Jewish stereotypes remain relatively underresearched in Scandinavia - even though antisemitic stereotypes have been present and flourishing in the North ever since the arrival of Christianity, and long before the arrival of the first Jewish communities.This volume aims to help bring the study of antisemitism to the fore, from the medieval period to the present day. Contributors from all the Nordic countries describe the status of as well as the challenges and desiderata for the study of antisemitism in their respective countries.  aIssued also in print.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aThis eBook is made available Open Access under a CC BY-NC-ND 4.0 license: uhttps://creativecommons.org/licenses/by-nc-nd/4.0 uhttps://www.degruyter.com/dg/page/open-access-policy  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 28. Feb 2023) 0aAntisemitismxHistoriography. 0aAntisemitismxResearchzScandinavia. 0aAntisemitismzScandinaviaxHistoriography. 0aAntisemitismzScandinaviaxHistory. 0aAntisemitismzScandinavia. 0aJewszScandinaviaxHistory. 4aAntisemitismus. 4aJudaistik. 4aNordische Geschichte. 7aHISTORY / Jewish.2bisacsh  aAnti-Semitism without Jews.  aAntisemitism Studies.  aNordic history.1 aAdams, Jonathan, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAdams, Jonathan, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aAhonen, Paavo, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBak, Sofie Lene, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCole, Richard, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDencik, Lars, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGaini, Firouz, econtributor.4ctb4htt